{"id":"astro-ph/9812148","submitter":"Martin Hardcastle","authors":"M. J. Hardcastle, D. M. Worrall and M. Birkinshaw","title":"Extended X-ray emission from the BL Lac object PKS 0521-365","comments":"10 pages, 5 figures, to appear in MNRAS","journal-ref":"Mon.Not.Roy.Astron.Soc. 305 (1999) 246","doi":"10.1046/j.1365-8711.1999.02353.x","report-no":"Bristol Astrophysics Preprint #37","categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Models that seek to unify BL Lacs and low-power radio galaxies predict that\nthe two types of object should show similar isotropically emitted X-ray\nemission. Testing this is usually limited by difficulties in separating strong\nX-ray emission from a BL Lac nucleus and surrounding low-surface brightness\nemission. In this paper we report ROSAT HRI observations of the z=0.055 BL Lac\nobject PKS 0521-365. We are able to separate a luminous extended X-ray\ncomponent from the bright nucleus. Using a new radio map, we show that it is\nunlikely that the extended emission is due to inverse-Compton scattering of\nphotons from the active nucleus, and instead interpret it as thermal emission\nfrom dense, rapidly cooling gas. This is a more extreme environment than is\nfound in typical FRI radio galaxies, and may pose a problem for unified models.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 8 Dec 1998 17:07:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
